By Zhang Diyang, southern weekend reporter

Southern weekend staff writer Zheng Yiling

Editor in chief | Wu Xiaoyu

On January 19,2020, Tongji Medical College Student Li Wen received a notice from her school asking all interns to take an early holiday and go home.

She was an intern working as a nurse at the Wuhan Union Hospital. Two days earlier, she had just been transferred out of radiology, also transferred to another department, along with all the interns in radiology.

No one was told the reason for the adjustment. It wasn't until the next night that she saw Zhong Nanshan's comment on the CCTV link that COVID-19 pneumonia was "passed from person to person" that she had an epiphany.

Little did she know, however, that the case cited by the Zhong Nanshan, Florida -- 14 medical staff were infected while nursing a patient -- occurred at Concorde Hospital, where she was an intern.

They were the first known cases of infection among health care workers in the outbreak, which marked a turning point in the epidemic's prevention and control on Jan. 20.

Health care workers are in serious condition in this outbreak. On the afternoon of February 14, Zeng Yixin, deputy director of the National Health Commission, said at a State Council news conference that as of 2400 hours on February 11, a total of 1,716 confirmed cases had been reported by medical personnel across the country, including six deaths. Of these, 1,102 confirmed cases have been reported by medical staff in Wuhan.

As of Jan. 28,57 of the hospital's 138 patients, 40 of whom were health care workers, had nosocomial infections, according to the Jama article by Peng Zhiyong, director of the Department of Critical Care Medicine at Jama.

In a chart released on February 3 showing the number of confirmed cases reported to Wuhan Medical Staff, Concorde ranked first with more than 100 cases.

The 14 medical staff were relatively lucky and were discharged from the hospital in three batches by 5 February. From the ward to take a direct elevator down the stairs, they made a victory sign.

Even though she knew about the outbreak, when she returned home for the required early holiday, Li could never have predicted that the hospital would soon be under national attention because of problems such as infection in medical care and urgent supplies.

1
In mid-january, the mood was "off" 

1

###In mid-january, the mood was "off" 

Before Zhong Nanshan's CCTV connection, no doctor or teacher had explicitly told the interns of the severity of the outbreak, but Li recalled that she sensed something "wrong" in the hospital's details.

Beginning in mid January, the respiratory medicine nurse teacher repeatedly urged her to protect herself and keep her mask on. From then on, she noticed, nurses were wearing blue hats instead of the usual nurse's hats, which required a full covering of hair.

During her internship, Li recalled to the southern weekend reporter, three fever patients in the respiratory department lived in the next ward, and doctors and nurses wore protective clothing when they entered the wards, and interns were asked not to enter the isolation ward. "interns get nervous every time they see a teacher in a protective suit. "

A day after Zhong Nanshan's CCTV connection, Zhou Xianwang, the mayor of Wuhan, said in an interview with CCTV that a patient in the Department of Neurosurgery at Concorde Hospital had developed fever after surgery and that 14 health care workers had been infected. "The lesson is profound, " Zhou said. "It has to do with the fact that our understanding of the harm and spread of the virus did not reach such a high level from the beginning. "

"because of our infection, academician Zhong Nanshan confirmed in his research that 'the virus can be transmitted from person to person, ' and it can be said that our diagnosis has redefined public awareness of the virus, " one of the infected nurses wrote in a social media post.

Another sick nurse developed fatigue, muscle soreness and chills at 6 a.m. on January 13, after taking care of a highly suspected patient on the night shift on January 12. By 2 p.m. , her temperature was 38.3 degrees Celsius, so began to draw blood, check CT, a variety of indicators are highly suspicious performance. The nurse said she was already wearing an N95 mask but no protective clothing while caring for suspected patients.

Protective Equipment is critical, but in the early days of the epidemic, almost all hospitals did not pay enough attention. A quarantine officer on board the Diamond Princess, which was quarantined in Port of Yokohama, Japan, was found to be infected. The officer had been carrying out a passenger questionnaire recall inside the ship, during which he wore surgical gloves and frequently disinfected his hands, but he was also not wearing protective clothing or goggles.

Until nearly a week later, on Jan. 19, the hospital had a kit that tested positive for nucleic acid, the infected nurse said. She entered the quarantine area with all kinds of uneasy mood, found together with a dozen colleagues, we are the first batch of confirmed medical staff, "is not alone. ".

One of the first doctors to be diagnosed was a neurosurgeon surnamed Zheng. "As a patient, I was really scared and didn't want to admit it, " he said in an article published on the Wuhan Union Hospital. But as a doctor, he was well aware that he might have been "hit. " Started isolating himself from his family.

Also confirmed with the batch of Union Hospital Emergency Department Director Zhang Jinnong. He experienced SARS, experienced, is the Peking Union Medical College Hospital on December 31,2019 set up the deputy head of the expert group to deal with the epidemic, mainly responsible for the development of clinical treatment programs and optimize the treatment process.

He chose to be treated in isolation at home, where he continued to review films, discuss cases, direct consultations, and draft the Wuhan Union Hospital and instructions for the COVID-19, the scheme was later widely disseminated on the Internet.

As the outbreak has progressed, there have been additional illnesses among Concorde's medical staff, but more accurate statistics are currently unavailable. "The only thing they could do was to keep telling the patients, 'masks, masks, you have to buy masks and wear masks, ' " one of the doctors told China News Weekly

On February 11,2020, the Guangdong medical team, the forward ICU team of Wuhan, held a remote video consultation with the First Affiliated Hospital of the Guangzhou Medical University at the Wuhan Union Hospital. (Xinhua News Agency / Photo)

2
From two doctors to four doctors to eight doctors

2

###From two doctors to four doctors to eight doctors

Liwen came here as an intern with admiration. "Concorde is very good. It's one of the top hospitals in the country. Doctors and teachers are very professional. It would be nice to work there after graduation. "

"Concord" is the "gold-lettered signboard" in the medical field of China. The Wuhan Union Hospital boasts on its website that it is now the largest of the country's top three health care brands. Founded in 1866 by the English Missionary Griffith John, the hospital was renamed Hankou Yan Chai Hospital and in 1928 it was renamed Hankou Union Hospital. In 2000, with its affiliated Tongji Medical University merged into the newly formed Huazhong University of Science and Technology.

Concord is also one of the largest hospitals in Wuhan. In terms of major medical indicators, the hospital is China's top general hospital: 6,028,000 outpatient and emergency visits, 255,000 hospital stays and more than 120,000 surgeries annually. The Wuhan Union Hospital ranks 12th in the country in the 2018 ranking of Chinese hospitals by the Institute of Hospital Management of Fudan University.

Ms. Li was particularly impressed by the bedside manner of medical staff. "teachers talk to patients with smiles no matter how tired they are, " she said, reversing her stereotype of doctors. Ms. Li was also struck by a sense of professionalism: "nurses check patients' names, beds and medications over and over again. ".

The outbreak has put this top-tier hospital on edge as never before.

The hospital is one of more than 60 hospitals in Wuhan with fever clinics. The West Wing of the hospital, designated by Wuhan as one of the third designated hospitals for fever patients, has become a front-line "battle field" for epidemic prevention and treatment.

On 31 December 2019, when the expert group was formed, Concordia decided to establish an isolation zone for respiratory infectious diseases.

The hospital is less than 4 km from the South China Seafood Market, where the outbreak is thought to have originated. With the outbreak, up to nine hundred patients a day came to the hospital's fever clinic, Caixin Media reported. But there was no respiratory ward here.

The entire first floor of the infectious diseases building was converted to a respiratory infectious disease ward. It soon filled up, and the second, third, and fourth floors became respiratory tract infection wards. Nearly thirty doctors were running low, and the hospital mobilized its internal medicine resources, especially the physicians in the smoking and emergency departments, to work shifts.

Originally the door hanging "expert clinic" of the clinic, all used as a fever clinic. The Hall of the Physical Examination Center has also become the infusion hall of the Fever Clinic.

Dr. Peric Lee, who works at the fever clinic, said in an interview that there are about 400 numbers a day, going from two to four, then to eight, working three shifts and 24 hours a day.

In order to prevent cross-infection of patients and cause wider spread, the hospital later closed the fever clinic and sent a team of medical experts to the designated hospitals to carry out diagnosis and treatment, medical Measures in fever clinics and isolation wards and all corresponding patients were transferred.

Pediatrician Lin Ming, who was pulled to the adult fever clinic, shared on the micro-headline that he eats more at breakfast to save on his protective clothing, and he doesn't eat until he takes it off after work.

"lived for more than 30 years, " Lin Ming also put on diapers for the first time, but he soon found that work can not be distracted, can not pee, and no longer wear.

There will be times of mourning. On the night of February 1, Lin Ming received a phone call from the director of the fever clinic. "Two brothers collapsed with fever. " After that, his night shift had to be adjusted from 8 p.m. to 8 a.m, "The director and I were silent on the phone until he said 'take care' and hung up. "

Chohan, deputy director of respiratory medicine at the Xuanwu Hospital, Capital Medical University, with colleagues at the Wuhan Union Hospital, Feb. 8,2020. (Xinhua News Agency / Photo)

After "supplies are not in a hurry, they are gone. "

3

###After "supplies are not in a hurry, they are gone. "

13 kilometers away, the Peking Union Medical College West Hospital, designated as the third group of new pneumonia designated hospitals, has transformed its inpatient building into a specialized inpatient building at the end of January. Medical teams from Beijing, Shaanxi, Heilongjiang and other places have come to help.

Beijing Chaoyang Hospital Emergency Department Deputy Director Tang Ziren is to come to Beijing medical team members, he is also Chaoyang Hospital medical team leader.

Tang Ziren's name was known because it was written on a protective suit.

The out-of-town medical team is not familiar with, put on the protective clothing, it is more difficult to recognize, so, each in the protective clothing on the write his hospital and name, big words.

On January 30, Tang posted a photo of himself wearing protective gear on his microblog, saying, "although we can not eat or drink for nearly 10 hours every time we enter the ward, this is nothing compared to the suffering the people of Wuhan are going through. "

Many netizens found that Tang Ziren's trouser legs were suspected to be tied up with a yellow medical garbage bag, which was also printed with words. On the same day, users who identified themselves as the hospital's neurosurgeons posted on Weibo that the hospital's supplies were "not in an emergency, they are gone, " raising public concern about the hospital's supplies.

On January 31, some netizens posted photos saying that due to the shortage of materials, the first-line medical staff of the West Hospital of the Union Medical College made protective clothing and face masks with yellow garbage bags and other materials. In response, the Wuhan Union Hospital later dismissed rumors that the pictures and articles were untrue.

Tang also denied making protective clothing. "whether it is masks or protective clothing, the supplies are still relatively sufficient at present, and at least the people on the front line can certainly be guaranteed, " he told southern weekend reporters during the connection. Tang Ziren said that the rescue work was on track, is Proceeding in an orderly fashion.

The Wuhan Union Hospital was indeed the first hospital in the outbreak to issue a public donation notice. On January 23,2020, the hospital issued a public notice to accept donations of love, said the urgent need for goggles, N95 masks, surgical masks, protective clothing and other supplies.

That's the truth. Li Remembers that the N95 masks at the hospital were not enough by the end of her internship. On January 19, when her department went to get supplies, they were given only 10 N95 masks, and the main nurse told everyone to save them.

A tweet on the public account of the hospital also revealed the shortage of materials. On January 23, three doctors from the Otolaryngology Department of the hospital completed the transfer of infected patients to the Wuhan Red Cross Hospital. During the transfer, one of the doctors was left without a protective mask and had to replace it with goggles because of a shortage of supplies.

Sun Hui, Deputy Party secretary of the Union Medical College Hospital, said in an interview with CCTV that "supplies are tight, but not to the point of 'running out of food and ammunition. ' ". For example, as deputy party secretary in charge of fever clinics, Sun said he used to visit fever clinics every day, but did not go back after material constraints because he had to save protective clothing for first-line use.

Outside the line, other departments may also encounter fever and pneumonia patients, but their supply is very tight. "Masks and protective clothing are still not enough and can only be supplied in limited quantities, " Dr. Zhang Yi, a concord surgeon, told southern weekend. His department gives two N95 masks a day to doctors on duty and one a day to doctors off duty.

After the material condition of Xiehe attracted strong attention, the materials donated by people from all over poured into the hospital.

On January 30, the first supplies donated by the Huakede Alumni Association were delivered directly to the Union Hospital. He Shuo, Secretary General of the Huakede Alumni Association, told southern weekend that as soon as the Wuhan Union Hospital and Tongji hospitals were in short supply, they acted to buy supplies from Germany and ship them home. Both hospitals are affiliated to the Huazhong University of Science and Technology.

In addition to donating to the two hospitals of his Alma Mater, materials raised by the Huakede Alumni Association were sent to 64 hospitals in 16 cities in Hubei Province. He Shuo explained that they are in direct contact with every department of every hospital, and the materials donated to Concord Hospital alone have 20 different departments and different recipients.

As of February 2,40 units from nine provinces of the country have made targeted donations, all of which have been delivered directly to the hospital. On the afternoon of Feb. 1, a helicopter dropped into Xinhua Road Stadium in Wuhan, carrying 800 sets of protective clothing donated to the Union Medical College Hospital.

Zhang Yi told southern weekend that with the influx of donations, the hospital's shortage of supplies has improved, and Zhang Yi's department has a limited number of goggles, which had been used by several doctors in turn, everyone is now given one, and after each use, it is disinfected with alcohol and reapplied.

But Zhang Yi confirmed that many of the donations were not for medical use, and that hospitals received masks to protect themselves from dust and smog. But medical masks weren't enough, and Zhang Yi and his colleagues found a compromise: they stacked industrial N95 masks on top of medical surgical masks.

"Most of the doctors and nurses are optimistic that they will be able to talk and laugh through their face masks, " Zhang Yi said. Liwen also noticed that in the wechat circle of Xiehe medical, no one complained, but many people sent "Wuhan refueling" to give themselves encouragement.

However, the atmosphere of tension in the hospital building from time to time. A colleague of Zhang Yi's started having fever a few days ago, and there were more and more scenes of nurses getting emotional and crying under high pressure.

Zhang Yi and Liwen
